While it can be said that doing so alone does give you more control and authority over what is being done, it also compounds the work necessary for you to complete. If you work without any others, there's no one to delegate portions of the assignment to, and if you struggle in any of the areas, you have no one to look to for help. Yes, you don't have to worry about others not appreciating the way you work, but you lose an irreplacable level of assistance.

When I began working on developing games, I was so frustrated at many steps, I found myself unable to complete some portions of the game that would be considered simple for many in that area. Such as art, and marketing. I was unable to draw characters and map tiles, but when I got another friend of mine to help me work on it, we were able to complete things at an exponential pace in comparison to before. I had to sacrifice some of my creative authority, but in exchange, I got a project that was actually fun to work on, and put my foot in the door to my favorite hobby ever.

In conclusion, working alone has its advantages, as long as the scope of the project is one you can undertake alone. You have more say over the details, and some just prefer working this way. But, if you're undertaking something on a larger scale, a good teammate or two are irreplacable. You will almost always be able to more quickly produce higher quality outcomes if you work with others. => h
